flowRoot.flowPara: Is folding better than a ruler and compass for making geometric constructions? Can you fold a piece of paper into a model with a larger perimeter than the original square? Mathematicians and engineers have recently started to explore origami's mathematical underpinnings, uncovering the answers to these questions and many more.

Even though researchers are still at the cusp of understanding this ancient art form, origami principles are already seeing application in areas as diverse as biochemistry and satellite deployment. This is an exploration into the mathematical richness hidden in the everyday paper crane or airplane. Let us show you the math between the folds.

We have some important tools for determining flat foldability when a crease pattern only has one vertex (that is, all the creases intersect at a single point. For example, Kawasaki’s Theorem requires that a vertex is flat-foldable if and only if the sum of every other angle around the vertex is 180 degrees.

In this example, notice that the two angles marked in red (45 and 135) add up to 180 degrees and the other two angles (each 90 degrees) also add up to 180. This tells us that this pattern will fold flat.

A single vertex can be folded flat if and only if the sum of every other angle around the vertex is 180 degrees.
A single vertex can be folded flat if and only if the difference between the number of mountain folds and the number of valley folds is plus or minus 2.

One of the most important questions in origami is whether or not a given model can be folded. Generally, we want to know if something can fold flat – that is, if the model can be pressed between the pages of a book without being crushed or introducing new creases.

text.tspan: How do we tell if a crease pattern can be folded?

flowRoot.flowPara: Can we tell if a given crease pattern can be folded flat? Or more generally, if it can be folded at all? There are two important conditions that let us know when a crease pattern can be folded flat: Kawasaki's and Maekawa's theorems.
Note that these are necessary but not sufficient conditions for flat foldability; there are some crease patterns that satisfy these conditions but still cannot fold flat.

Sometimes, a model can't be folded flat, but it can be folded in a 3D form. This flower is an example – you can see that if you tried to press it in a book, it would get crushed. Unfortunately, it's much more difficult to study 3D foldability. It isn't clear how to tell from the crease pattern that the flower won't fold flat.
Here's an example of a crease pattern that can't be folded flat at all. In fact, it can't even be folded in a 3D form without curving the paper (unlike the flower above).
Notice that this crease pattern satisfies Maekawa's and Kawasaki's theorems--the fact that it still can't be folded flat demonstrates why these theorems are not sufficient.

text.tspan: What do maps have to do with Origami?

flowRoot.flowPara: Maps are crease patterns with evenly spaced horizontal and vertical lines. Why study maps? They are easier to deal with than general crease patterns and may give us clues on how to study foldability for more complicated models. When we look at map crease patterns, we generally want to know if they can be folded flat.

Unfortunately, studying maps is still difficult. It takes a computer a long time to figure out if a map crease pattern can be folded flat – in fact, the best way mathematicians know of is to simply try every possible way of folding the map and seeing if any way works.

Here are two map crease patterns. One of them can be folded flat, and the other can't. On the table to the left, you can try to find out which one can be folded. Remember that red lines are mountian folds and must point up; and blue lines are valley folds, and point down.
Mountain Fold
Valley Fold

text.tspan: What do Napkins have to do with Origami?

flowRoot.flowPara: While the mathematics of origami does have important real-life applications, there are a number of more recreational questions about Origami that have equally interesting answers. The napkin folding problem is one such recreational problem.

Can you fold a piece of paper (or a napkin) into a shape that is has a larger perimeter (distance around the outside) than the original square? Go ahead and to to do it at the table to the left. It seems impossible!
It might be surprising, but it turns out you can. Take a look at the model to the left--it has slightly greater perimeter than the starting square.
In fact, if our paper is thin enough, we can get an arbitrarily large perimeter! We can do this by tiling this crease pattern in a grid.

There is a corresponding set of axioms for doing geometry with origami. These formalize what we can accomplish by folding lines on a piece of paper. There are seven axioms, four of which we include here.

Ancient Greeks mathematicians were deeply interested in using basic drawing tools--in particular, a compass and straightedge--to make accurate geometric figures. However, they realized that certain shapes were very difficult to draw accurately using these tools. It turns out that if they had used origami to make their marks, they would have been more successful.
The famous Greek mathematician Euclid (c. 300 BCE) produced a set of rules, known as axioms, that formalize what we intuitively think is true about doing geometry with a compass and straightedge.
